🌍 1. Sabse Pehle: Scope Kya Hota Hai?

Scope = Variables kaha accessible hain (kahan use kar sakte ho).

Matlab:
Agar variable ek jagah declare hua hai, toh JavaScript decide karega usko kaha tak access kar sakte ho.

🧠 Types of Scope in JavaScript:
📦 Global Scope
let name = "Rounak";

function greet() {
    console.log(name);
}

greet(); // Rounak
🏠 Function Scope
function test() {
    let age = 21;
    console.log(age);
}

test(); // 21
// console.log(age); ❌ Error
📂 Block Scope (let, const)
{
    let city = "Delhi";
    console.log(city); // Delhi
}

// console.log(city); ❌ Error
🔥 2. Lexical Scoping Kya Hai?
📖 Definition:

Lexical = Code likhne ki position
Matlab function ka scope uski location se decide hota hai, na ki call kaha hua.

👉 Inner function outer function ke variables access kar sakta hai.

🎯 Example:
function outer() {
    let outerVar = "I am outer";

    function inner() {
        console.log(outerVar);
    }

    inner();
}

outer();
📌 Output:
I am outer
🧠 Why?

Kyuki inner() physically outer() ke andar likha hua hai.

🏗️ Visual Representation:
Global Scope
   |
   |-- outer()
         |
         |-- inner()

👉 inner() apna + outer ka access karega
👉 outer global ka bhi access karega

❌ Reverse Possible Nahi:

Outer inner ke variables access nahi kar sakta.

function outer() {
    function inner() {
        let secret = "Hidden";
    }

    // console.log(secret); ❌ Error
}
🎁 3. Closure Kya Hota Hai?
📖 Definition:

Closure = Function + Uska Lexical Environment

Matlab:
Jab function return ho jaye, tab bhi woh apne outer variables ko yaad rakhta hai.

🧠 Simple Words:

“Function apne parent scope ki memory lekar chalta hai.”

🎯 Example:
function parent() {
    let count = 0;

    return function child() {
        count++;
        console.log(count);
    };
}

const counter = parent();

counter(); // 1
counter(); // 2
counter(); // 3
🔥 Output:
1
2
3
🤯 Important:

parent() execute ho chuka hai...
Normally variables destroy ho jane chahiye...

BUT child() ne count ko memory me preserve rakha
👉 THIS IS CLOSURE

🏦 Real Life Analogy:

Imagine:
Parent = Bank locker
Child = Key

Bank band ho gaya but key ke paas access hai 🔐

🛠️ Step-by-Step Execution:
const counter = parent();
Step 1:

parent() runs
count = 0

Step 2:

child function returned

Step 3:

counter now stores child function + count memory

📌 Memory:
counter = {
   function: child(),
   count: 0
}
🚨 Important Interview Line:
“Closure is created every time a function is created.”
🎯 Another Example:
function greeting(message) {
    return function(name) {
        console.log(message + ", " + name);
    };
}

const sayHello = greeting("Hello");

sayHello("Rounak");
Output:
Hello, Rounak
🔥 Why?

sayHello remembers "Hello"

🧪 4. Common Interview Trap (var issue)
for (var i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
    setTimeout(function() {
        console.log(i);
    }, 1000);
}
😵 Output:
4
4
4
❓ Why?

Because var is function scoped
Sab functions same i share karte hain.

✅ Fix with let
for (let i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
    setTimeout(function() {
        console.log(i);
    }, 1000);
}
Output:
1
2
3
🔥 Because:

let har iteration ka separate scope banata hai.

🛠️ Fix using Closure:
for (var i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
    (function(j) {
        setTimeout(function() {
            console.log(j);
        }, 1000);
    })(i);
}
🎯 5. Practical Uses of Closures
🔒 Data Privacy / Encapsulation
function secretPassword() {
    let password = "12345";

    return function() {
        console.log(password);
    };
}

const getPassword = secretPassword();
getPassword();
🧮 Counter
function createCounter() {
    let count = 0;

    return {
        increment: function() {
            count++;
            console.log(count);
        },
        decrement: function() {
            count--;
            console.log(count);
        }
    };
}

const counter = createCounter();

counter.increment(); // 1
counter.increment(); // 2
counter.decrement(); // 1
🌟 Module Pattern
const bankAccount = (function() {
    let balance = 1000;

    return {
        deposit: function(amount) {
            balance += amount;
            console.log(balance);
        },
        withdraw: function(amount) {
            balance -= amount;
            console.log(balance);
        }
    };
})();

bankAccount.deposit(500); // 1500
⚡ 6. Closure Advantages
✅ Advantages:
🔐 Private Variables
💾 Data Persistence
🏗️ Function Factories
📦 Memoization
🎛️ Event Handlers
❌ Disadvantages:
🐢 More Memory Usage
🧠 Hard Debugging
🚮 Memory Leaks if misused
🧠 7. Lexical Scope vs Closure
Feature	Lexical Scope	Closure
Based on	Where function is written	Function + remembered variables
Memory	Normal scope chain	Preserved even after parent ends
Purpose	Variable access rules	Data persistence
🎯 Easy Difference:
Lexical Scope:

“Function kahan likha hai?”

Closure:

“Function kya yaad rakhta hai?”

